To give credit to Verstappen, in china, carlos crashed in quali, sesion red flagged, carlos recovered on his own and crawled to the pits. FiA added a clarification to the rules, that a car isnt allowed to receive help from a marshall and contiue participating in the sesion. (pushing it on track etc. aka the marshall cant directly touch the car, so Albon in Baku was ok). Here Lance crashed, tried to recover and didnt. Sesion should have been immediatelly red flagged no matter if the driver is "MaYbE" able to recover.

Fan of Ferrari and fair play

text_display: Tom seems like a quiet, methodical kind of guy who you could easily talk to for hours, and I'm glad he's with McLaren. WCC 2024!!!

text_original:
A lot of the podcasts leading up to the Austin race are principally people sniffing their own farts, I've cut all of them off after about 5 minutes.
Listening to Tom interviewing Tom is in an entirely different league.  Tom Stallard is clearly a talented communicator, very precise yet easy to listen to.  He seems to have maintained a sense of humility and objectivity from his Olympic rowing days.  
I loved his comment regarding both sides of the garage, and how he measured success in performance development.
Tom C's questions are excellent too, and he isn't forcing himself into the interview unnecessarily.
Slightly surprised that talk about drivers made no reference to Fernando Alonso (only slightly).  With many of Tom S' references to team building & leadership and radio communications there would have been a lot to gloss over!!

text_original:
Checo didn't really hold his line, he was point on the line exit and when Sainz come closer he moved with his right tyre over that same line before contact happened, he gave Sainz some extra space (about 1 meter) but Sainz continued steering to the middle.
Drivers are obliged to give each other space, Sainz had that before Checo gave him some more but Sainz just wanted the ideal line the full slipstream with a better position for the next corner.
Never read any rulings that a driver should give up his favorable position if another really wanted to have that spot.
Charles knew Checo was there btw, can't tell me otherwise, he should have seen him in the corner itself and you can see him checking his mirror multiple times while drifting sideways, he just assumed Checo would hand him the better place on the road if he squeezed him more.
Funny btw that if Checo had hit LeClerc because he drifted to far, Checo would be at fault, but if Sainz hits Checo because he drifted to far, Checo's at fault...really can't agree with this one.
Imo Sainz was more at fault eventhough Checo could have avoided it by letting himself be pushed back and give up the duel, why? Because Charles claimed ground that wasn't his and he could have stopped when he saw that Checo gave him a little to avoid the contact but didn't move away completely.
Glad no penalties were handed out though, both drivers already lost this race here and a penalty for the next wouldn't help the other driver, think penalties for subsequent races should only happen if the action was simply far beyond reasonable.

text_original: I believe the commentator's viewpoint is inaccurate and not supported by the facts. He states in his argument to fault Checo that Sainz is ahead, which is true, but in F1, it is more important who has the speed advantage and the race line. No driver is entitled to force his way into another car's race line (Always leave room Fernando Alonso ); simply put, you do not have to give way to your race line to provide a better outcome for another driver. In a previous similar case, when Checo overtook Lecler, Lecler didn't move an inch to give way to Checo... that is fair racing; don't expect anybody to move their car to facilitate your overtaking.
text_display: I believe the commentator's viewpoint is inaccurate and not supported by the facts. He states in his argument to fault Checo that Sainz is ahead, which is true, but in F1, it is more important who has the speed advantage and the race line. No driver is entitled to force his way into another car's race line (Always leave room Fernando Alonso ); simply put, you do not have to give way to your race line to provide a better outcome for another driver. In a previous similar case, when Checo overtook Lecler, Lecler didn't move an inch to give way to Checo... that is fair racing; don't expect anybody to move their car to facilitate your overtaking.

text_original:
Outstanding performance by Stroll!What a race. Can watch again and again. Lando should see how Max patiently works his way up in a race with no DRS. It is only in the 43rd lap he passed for P1. How he decided to stay out and took the chance which converted to victory.

See how drivers were spinning out. How many times in how many races Max has anticipated and corrected his spins immediately to continue racing? Didn't make single mistake in this race.

What a pleasure to watch a master at work. Wonderful race. Followed by an emotional and delightful podium. Followed by possibly the best FIA post race conference in the entire year. Jovial,relaxed, nice questions, some memories and experiences shared by the drivers. No British press.This masterclass will be remembered for generations to come. And it didn't even show that Max was driving fastest laps non-stop.

text_original:
A question for all my fellow motor/gearheads, racing fans, and sim-racers.
There's no right or wrong answer, I'm just looking for opinions.
Which strategy do you favor: 
1 -- A one-stopper that requires you to be as kind to the tires as you can for as long as you can, sacrificing some speed in the hopes of gaining time at the end stages of the race, or
2 -- A two-stopper that allows you to go as fast as you can -- basically doing quali laps for the whole race?

1 is obviously safer lap-by-lap, but man, does it ever _feel_ slow. This method definitely requires patience.
2 is a lot more dangerous since you're dancing on the razor's edge the entire time. One mistake, even a relatively minor one, can cost you many places at the end. And getting caught behind any traffic also puts a damper on your strategy, and possibly the outcome.

If you answer, can you say why you chose that way?
Thanks to any who play along.

Oh, and please give this comment a thumbs up so more eyes see it. I couldn't care less about the number of likes I get, but with more likes come more eyes, and hence, more potential answers. Thanks!

text_original:
Seeing inside story you see how drivers like Lewis and Max are simply on another level compared to the rest of the grid... 
Their sheer mental capacity to think 5-10 laps ahead while driving at nearly 200mph in such tricky conditions is why they've dominated the sport. As wonderful as drivers like Norris, Leclerc, and Russell are, I never see them being so strategic and mentally acute in races... Sainz has his moments of such brilliance but I feel Piastri is getting this better than Norris at Mclaren.

I know it's partly due to the insane profitability of Red Bull, a soda that charges 2-3 times what Coke does,  but how does a soft drink maker out-engineer (1) a company that has been an aerospace contractor, (2) the best known maker of sports cars, and (3) maybe the only company better known for high performance than Ferrari?

And at the time he was still fighting for the championship and winning races when he was involved in the pile up alongside Alonso at Spa 2012.

text_original: Sutil absolutely ANNIHILATED Trulliâ€™s entire argument and you can see Trulliâ€™s soul progressively dying as the argument goes on. I remember watching this live on the Speed Channel back when Bob Varsha, David Hobbs, Steve Matchett and Peter Windsor were still covering F1 in The States. The commentators would get together after the race and do a highlights reel of the race and do a few minute summery of their perspectives on various things in the race. David Hobbs and Steve Matchett were absolutely dying on the floor laughing while Bob Varsha was trying so desperately hard to not laugh and be diplomatic about it. It was so out of character for the other two that it just made this whole moment between Sutil and Trulli even funnier than it already was. Iâ€™ve desperately tried to find it on the internet and there doesnâ€™t seem to be a trace of it anywhereâ€¦ such a shame too.,. It was one of the funniest moments in F1 commentator history.
